      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my fiddle leaf fig is looking kinda sad and i think the roots are starting to poke out the bottom of the pot. im thinking about repotting it soon but im scared i'll kill it. what kind of soil should i use and how do i do it without shocking the plant too much?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fine, well-tempered, and slightly dampened soil is the key to keeping your fiddle leaf fig alive and happy, but you must be careful not to overdo it. If you repot too soon, the roots will be exposed to the air, which is like letting a goblin out of the house and letting them run around the garden without a fence.\n\nFirst, let's talk about the soil. You want something that is rich in nutrients but also drains well so the roots don't get stuck. A mix of potting soil, perlite, and peat moss is usually the best bet. Think of it like a cozy, warm house for your goblin friends; it should be soft enough to hug but firm enough to hold them.\n\nNow, about the roots poking out! This is a sign that the plant is ready for a new home, but you need to be gentle. Gently remove the plant from its current pot, making sure not to tug on the roots. If you see roots sticking out, that's your plant's way of saying, \"I need more space!\"\n\nWhen you repot it, use a pot that is slightly larger than the current one. Fill it with your new",
